# Analysis I mathematics still to be completed
#
# This is a comment-only ledger.  It is not a chapter, is not exported by
# litex.config, and contains no executable Litex declarations.
#
# Snapshot: 2026-07-21.  The book currently contains 45 direct `trust` sites,
# all in Chapters 8, 9, and 11.  Chapters 1-7 and 10, together with Appendix A,
# contain no direct `trust` statement.
#
# Each item names the theorem whose proof contains the hole, gives the current
# source line for quick lookup, states the missing mathematics, and says which
# source-facing result the hole supports.  Line numbers are secondary locators
# and may move as chapters are edited.
#
# Chapter 7 has no remaining direct `trust`.  Its cleanup exposed several
# reusable proof packages that are checked locally but may later belong in the
# standard library.  These are not current proof holes:
#
# - finite non-negative sums are monotone under finite-set inclusion, together
#   with injective finite reindexing and finite permutation-prefix transport;
# - mutually cofinal monotone partial-sum sequences have the same finite limit;
# - dyadic harmonic-block lower bounds and condensation-to-geometric rewrites;
# - paired even/odd induction for alternating finite tails;
# - finite telescoping products of consecutive ratios and the resulting
#   eventual ratio-to-nth-root bounds;
# - adapters between equivalent chapter-local and Chapter 6 limsup predicates.
#
# The ratio-test cleanup also corrected one over-strong intermediate statement:
# a ratio liminf above one need not give a finite root limsup, because upper
# spikes may be unbounded.  The checked proof now derives failure of the zero
# limit directly, which is exactly what the divergent ratio test requires.
#
# Chapter 8 — Infinite sets (15 direct trust sites)
#
# Nine former sites are now checked: countable union (using the explicit
# choice axiom), the two elementary finite-subsum bridges for nonnegative
# double series, swapped and column-first transport, one direction of Lemma
# 8.2.3, countability of nonzero support, bijection change of variables, and
# finite-total-order well-ordering.  The reusable finite reindexing and
# finite-set induction packages remain in the chapter as checked lemmas.
#
# Item 08-01 — Section 8.2; countable_set_series_sum_well_defined, trust at line 1926.
# Prove that two enumerations of one countably infinite set give the same
# absolutely convergent sum.  This is one of the three retained local bridges.
#
# Item 08-02 — Section 8.2; bounded_rectangles_and_capture_give_row_first_sum,
# trust at line 2199.  Construct all row sums, bound their finite partial sums by L,
# and use finite-support capture to prove that the iterated sum is exactly L.
# This is the analytic core of the nonnegative Fubini proof, not a reindexing
# wrapper; Tao leaves the gap steps to Exercise 8.2.5.
#
# Item 08-03 — Section 8.2; fubini_row_first_general_case, trust at line 2223.
# Apply the nonnegative case to positive and negative parts and recombine the
# two row-first sums.  This is the remaining signed Fubini argument.
#
# Item 08-04 — Section 8.2;
# bounded_finite_subsums_imply_countable_absolute_convergence, trust at line 2359.
# The statement is false with the current definition: an empty or finite X
# has bounded finite subsums but admits no bijection N_pos -> X.  Repair the
# countable-set-series interface so finite sets have a finite-sum branch, then
# prove the countably infinite branch by bounded nonnegative partial sums.
#
# Item 08-05 — Section 8.2; arbitrary_set_series_add, trust at line 2528.
# The current statement can fail when f and g cancel and the resulting support
# is finite or empty, because has_set_series_sum still demands a bijection from
# N_pos onto that support.  It depends on the same finite-support repair.
#
# Item 08-06 — Section 8.2; arbitrary_set_series_scalar_mul, trust at line 2535.
# The c = 0 case always has empty support, so the current conclusion is false.
# It depends on the same finite-support repair; c != 0 is then ordinary scalar
# transport of the support series.
#
# Item 08-07 — Section 8.2; arbitrary_set_series_disjoint_union, trust at line 2547.
# Interleave the two support enumerations, prove the merged series has sum
# L1 + L2, and combine the finite absolute-subsums.  This is a genuine series
# merge proof from Exercise 8.2.3.
#
# Item 08-08 — Section 8.2;
# positive_and_negative_parts_of_conditional_series_diverge, trust at line 2714.
# Show that convergence of either sign subseries together with convergence of
# the original series would force convergence of the absolute-value series.
# This is Exercise 8.2.4 and prepares the rearrangement construction.
#
# Item 08-09 — Section 8.2; riemann_rearrangement_theorem, trust at line 2739.
# Construct the alternating positive/negative selection permutation, prove its
# partial sums converge to the target, and retain non-absolute convergence.
# Tao leaves these details to Exercise 8.2.5.
#
# Item 08-10 — Section 8.3; has_binary_decimal_subset_sum, trust at line 2812.
# Prove existence and uniqueness of each subset's binary-decimal real sum.
# This is the second retained local bridge.
#
# Item 08-11 — Section 8.3; binary_decimal_subset_sum_is_injective, trust at line 2816.
# At the first differing digit, dominate the later binary tail.  This is the
# third retained local bridge.
#
# Item 08-12 — Section 8.5;
# good_chain_comparison_forward_from_exercise_8_5_13, trust at line 4816.
# Prove that every point of W minus Y strictly bounds Y.  This is one half of
# the source's entire Exercise 8.5.13 comparison argument.
#
# Item 08-13 — Section 8.5;
# good_chain_comparison_reverse_from_exercise_8_5_13, trust at line 4826.
# Prove the symmetric comparison for points of Y minus W.
#
# Item 08-14 — Section 8.5; good_chain_union_is_chain_with_minimum, trust at line 4836.
# Prove that the union of all good chains is itself well-ordered with x0 as
# minimum.  The source marks the union-order verification as "why?".
#
# Item 08-15 — Section 8.5; good_chain_union_has_no_strict_upper_bound,
# trust at line 4846.  Show that a chosen strict upper bound extends the union to a
# larger good chain, contradicting the definition of the union.
#
# Checked Chapter 8 patterns worth considering for the standard library later
# (these are not current proof holes):
#
# - reindex a finite subset through an injective/countable enumeration, and
#   realize an enumeration prefix as a finite image with the same sum;
# - compare a finite subsum of nonnegative terms with a convergent full sum;
# - choose one injective coding graph per member of a family and pair the
#   outer/inner codes to prove a countable union at most countable;
# - construct a finite subset of any prescribed size inside a nonfinite set;
# - strengthen finite-total-order induction to a least-element statement before
#   deriving the source's minimal-element formulation;
# - transport countable support and finite absolute subsums through a bijection,
#   and use coordinate-swap involutions for double-series views.
#
